Why your image doesn‚Äôt appear
Your src is not a direct image URL.
You copied the Google search link or the ‚Äúimage preview‚Äù URL, not the actual image file.
This URL doesn‚Äôt point directly to the image file, it points to a Google redirect page.
Browsers can‚Äôt display it as an image, so they fallback to showing the alt text: "An image of a cute cat".

Get the link:
The original image is hosted on... at: https://pethelpful.com/cats/top-10-cutest-cat-photos-of-all-time
To get the direct image URL, I did this:
Right-click on the image ‚Üí ‚ÄúOpen image in new tab‚Äù (or ‚ÄúCopy image address‚Äù depending on browser).
This gave the exact URL pointing to the image file, which ends in .jpg.


# when you use a full-size image from a website, it often loads at its original resolution, which can be huge. In your case, it‚Äôs something like 5200√ó3470 pixels! üòÖ
Make it smaller by width and height attributes
<img src="https://pethelpful.com/.image/c_fill,g_faces:center/MTk2NzY3MjA5ODc0MjY5ODI2/top-10-cutest-cat-photos-of-all-time.jpg"
     alt="An image of a cute cat"
     width="600">



